---
import MainLayout from '../../../layouts/MainLayout.astro';
import MotuSidebar from '../../../components/MotuSidebar.astro';
const title = 'Mixing and Effects';
---

<MainLayout title={title}>
  <div class="flex gap-8 items-start">
    <div class="w-[250px] flex-shrink-0">
      <MotuSidebar />
    </div>
    <article class="prose max-w-none">
      <h1>{title}</h1>
      <p>Source: <a href="https://motu.com/products/motuaudio/ultralite-mk3/mixing.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener">MOTU product page</a></p>

      <h2>On-Board DSP Mixer</h2>
      <p>The UltraLite-mk3's built-in DSP mixer operates at 32-bit floating-point precision entirely in hardware. Any input can be routed to any output at zero latency — the computer is completely bypassed in the signal path. This is the foundation of latency-free monitoring.</p>

      <h2>Zero-Latency Monitor Mix</h2>
      <p>When a vocalist is recording through the SM58, the standard DAW monitoring path (mic → MOTU → computer → DAW → MOTU → headphones) adds audible delay. The CueMix FX solution:</p>
      <ol>
        <li>In CueMix FX, create a direct send from Input 1 (SM58) to the Phones output bus — zero computer involvement.</li>
        <li>In Ableton, set the vocal Audio Track's Monitor to <strong>Off</strong> (or <strong>Auto</strong> with recording enabled). This prevents the computer-processed signal from doubling with the hardware monitor signal.</li>
        <li>The vocalist hears themselves with zero perceptible delay.</li>
      </ol>

      <h2>Separate Parallel Mixes</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Mix 1 (Main):</strong> flat, accurate monitoring signal to the HS7 studio monitors. Represents what's actually in the session without enhancement.</li>
        <li><strong>Mix 2 (Phones/Cue):</strong> customized headphone mix for the vocalist — their own voice louder (+6 dB relative to backing track), with a touch of CueMix Classic Reverb for comfort and feel during recording.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Standalone Mixer Mode</h2>
      <p>All CueMix FX mix settings are saved to the MOTU's internal flash memory. Disconnect the computer entirely — the UltraLite-mk3 operates as a standalone hardware mixer, retaining all your routing, levels, and effects settings. This is useful for live performance where a laptop isn't required.</p>

      <figure>
        <img src="/assets/motu/ultralite-mk3/mixing.jpg" alt="CueMix and mixing overview for the UltraLite-mk3" />
        <figcaption>Mixing and effects section from the UltraLite-mk3 product materials.</figcaption>
      </figure>
    </article>
  </div>
</MainLayout>
